Hi Tim,

All well here, thanks. Hot and dry, as I'm sure it is with you, too!

Thanks for the update about v6.0a - that's great. I will gradually try and start integrating the changes in the Python version. I've been refactoring the code and adding some FAO56 modules which we will use initially in CHANSE. Essentially here I try and keep the hydrology the same as in AquaCrop, but crop yield is based on the single coefficient method. In the next few weeks we will try and couple this with a groundwater model from BGS. At some point it would be great to discuss further with you your ideas for computing yield a priori (i.e. not relying on estimates of potential yield, as in FAO56), while bypassing some of the more parameter intensive aspects of AquaCrop.

Regarding salinity and fertility, I guess my inclination would be to include them and turn them off by default, with due warning about the scientific credibility of the routines. From a software/model development point of view that is at least a starting point and provides an entry point to the code base for anyone to make improvements in the future. Providing them also means that the methods can be more widely tested and improved. 

